# Linting Workflow

After any substantive edit to a `.ts` or `.tsx` file:
1. Run `npm run lint:fix` in the relevant app directory — auto-fixes what it can (unused imports, etc.)
2. Use `ReadLints` on edited files to catch anything the linter can't auto-fix
3. Fix remaining errors manually
4. Never leave a task marked complete with outstanding lint errors

# No Conditional Spread

Never use `...(condition && { key: value })` to build objects conditionally. It is hard to read and obscures intent.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
await prisma.user.update({
  data: {
    ...(data.role !== undefined && { role: data.role }),
    ...(data.rosterIds !== undefined && { rosterIds: data.rosterIds }),
  },
});

// ✅ GOOD
const updates: Prisma.UserUpdateInput = {};
if (data.role !== undefined) updates.role = data.role;
if (data.rosterIds !== undefined) updates.rosterIds = data.rosterIds;
await prisma.user.update({ data: updates });
```

# Express Route Params

`req.params["id"]` types as `string | string[]` — `!` does not narrow this. Always cast to `string`:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const id = BigInt(req.params["id"]!);

// ✅ GOOD
const id = BigInt(req.params["id"] as string);
```

# Type Imports

Always use `import type` for type-only imports. Enforced by `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-imports`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
import { RequestHandler } from "express";

// ✅ GOOD
import type { RequestHandler } from "express";
```

